<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   TANJUG Reports on Rugova's U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2503142494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1228 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2503142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pristina, 25 March (TANJUG) -- Ibrahim Rugova, 
president of the Democratic Alliance of Kosovo [DSK] and 
self-proclaimed president of the so-called "republic of Kosovo," 
today described his visit to the United States as an "important 
visit." 
  At a news conference he failed to comment at length on the 
activities of his "prime minister" Bujar Bukosi in Washington, 
where this man had requested support from U.S. officials for 
separatist demands for the secession of Kosovo and Metohija from 
Serbia, but stressed that these activities were "within the 
framework of regular visits to and contacts with the United 
States." 
  The DSK president welcomed the Belgian foreign minister's 
visit to Tirana, dubbing as "press speculations" hints that 
Willy Claes would convey to Albanian President Sali Berisha the 
European Union's stance on the inviolability of borders and its 
position that Kosmet [Kosovo and Metohija] Albanians can seek a 
solution only within the context of autonomy. 
  Not ruling out the possibility that Claes and Berisha could 
examine all options for resolving the Kosmet issue, Rugova 
declared that, as "president of Kosovo," a title he had bestowed 
upon himself, he would take into account the will of the 
Albanians expressed at the referendum. 
  This, he said, means "an independent and neutral Kosovo" 
which, in his view, is "a compromise solution acceptable to both 
Albanians and Serbs." 
  He described the Yugoslav Government's decision not to allow 
foreign missions in Kosovo as "confirmation of a stubborn and 
damaging policy pursued by the Serbian authorities." 
  Speaking about the German authorities' intention to deport 
several thousand Yugoslav refugees, mostly Albanians, Rugova 
said that he had received official assurances that this would be 
done "as painlessly as possible," but he failed to elaborate on 
what this meant. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

