<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Srpska Assembly Discusses Future of Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2503160894 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2503160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mirjana Kusmuk] </F>
  [Text] The assembly of the Srpska republic has continued 
its session in Pale. SRNA journalist Mirjana Kusmuk reports: 
  [Kusmuk] The 39th session of the people's assembly of the 
Srpska republic continued in Pale at about 1100 this morning. 
After government ministers presented their reports, the deputies 
started to debate them behind closed doors. During the 15-minute 
break, the president of the Srpska republic [Radovan Karadzic] 
expressed a doubt in the replacement of the government, assuming 
that the assembly will decide to reshuffle it soon. The 
government will be made more dynamic and new posts will be 
created, those of deputies and assistants. The government will 
also be requested to work faster. This will have to produce 
results, Karadzic said. 
  The assembly of the Srpska republic should today send a 
letter to UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali regarding the UN 
decision to send Turkish troops to the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. According to Karadzic, judging by the 
prevailing mood in the assembly, the aforementioned letter will 
also contain a statement that by adopting this decision the 
Security Council has assumed responsibility for yet another 
dangerous precedent in the case of the former Yugoslavia, and 
that this represented the most direct responsibility for the 
possible spread of the war. 
  Commenting on the platform for the continuation of the peace 
negotiations adopted yesterday, Karadzic stressed that the 
Serbian side would continue to negotiate with the Croats and the 
Muslims on some kind of links under certain conditions, but that 
it will not agree to the imposition of any solutions. 
  A doubt was expressed that the conditions existed for our 
entry in the Muslim-Croat federation. However, we have not 
received any official offer to join them, Karadzic said. 
  The assembly session is still in progress. The reports of 
the republican ministries are being discussed behind closed 
doors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

