<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Territory Must Be Recaptured </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2503211094 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1900 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2503211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] A two-day session of the main committee 
of the Party of Democratic Action [SDA] opened in Sarajevo. In 
addition to the president of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, 
Alija Izetbegovic, the session is being attended by 
representatives of the highest state bodies and political, 
religious, and military life of the city and the state. 
  In a report on the work of the SDA so far, Party Chairman 
Mirsad Ceman gave a brief summary of the activity of the SDA, 
one of the rare organizations which was prepared for the 
aggression against Bosnia-Herzegovina and which contributed 
fully -- in political, military, and all other spheres -- to the 
defense of our homeland and the Bosniak Muslim nation whose 
political interests it represents. The SDA has fully responded 
to the historic challenge and it therefore represents a strong 
political basis and a guarantee for the survival and freedom of 
the Bosniak Muslims. 
  Speaking about Bosnia, President Izetbegovic said that good 
and evil, reason and madness came into conflict here. 
  [Begin Izetbegovic recording] I have noticed over the past 
two years of this war that the world has slowly divided into 
those who are for and those who are against Bosnia. There are 
almost no more neutral people. They have either been for or 
against Bosnia, and no one has remained uninvolved. 
  When you analyze that division, you can see that everything 
that was good, thank God, sided with us. I have noticed this 
speaking, for example, about governments in a country. Their 
sleek politicians placed themselves on the other side, but the 
free-thinking people in that country -- [word indistinct] all 
those idealists, romantics, poets, artists -- they were all on 
our side. The whole of the Muslim world was on our side, but 
that is a special case. Everything good in the Western world 
sided with us. [end recording] 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Bosnia will be a country of law 
and order, Izetbegovic went on to say. At the same time, it 
will be governed in such a way that a genocide against Bosniak 
Muslims will never again occur. Despite the fact that they have 
lost most people for Bosnia's freedom, they will not give up the 
struggle to recover the captured territories. 
  [Begin Izetbegovic recording] Our people currently living in 
Germany or Croatia must be able to return to their villages near 
Zvornik. There is no negotiating there. There is no 
negotiating there. [applause] That is a practical, everyday, 
political reason. There is also a moral reason. Could we 
possibly give them [Serbs] those territories as a reward for 
(?their job) of having killed us -- please keep it as a reward. 
We will not allow that. [end recording] 
  [Correspondent] As part of the second item of the agenda, 
which has not started yet, following a report by Prime Minister 
Haris Silajdzic on the recently signed agreement with the 
Croats, seven more reports will be submitted: on the functioning 
of state bodies, foreign policy, information, refugees, army, 
veterans' issues, and economic reconstruction of the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

