<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic Meets With Iranian Envoy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2703223294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2703223294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks are recorded] </F>
  [Text] Alija Izetbegovic, president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, today had talks with Mohammad 
Javad Asayesh-Zarebi, ambassador of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
to Bosnia-Herzegovina, about the current situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the relations between the two countries. 
After the talks Ambassador Asayesh-Zarebi and President 
Izetbegovic made the following statements: 
  [Asayesh-Zarebi, in Persian with superimposed Serbo-Croatian 
translation] "We had very useful talks with President 
Izetbegovic. We are hoping that the initiated peace talks will 
bring peace. The Islamic Republic of Iran is pleased with the 
newly developing situation, [words indistinct] why it had not 
been done earlier. The negotiations that were conducted between 
Muslims, Croats, and Serbs should end with real peace. We are 
hoping that the borders are not going to be changed. We would 
like to thank the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government and the 
presidency since they are trying hard to [word indistinct] 
Bosnia-Herzegovina as little as possible." 
  [Izetbegovic] ``I had talks with Iranian Ambassador Mohammad 
Javad Asayesh-Zarebi; first of all, I informed him about the 
last round our of negotiations, about the Washington agreement. 
I am pleased to have concluded that Iran also supports our 
efforts to that effect, which is a path toward the restoration 
of peace here. We also examined what Iran can do in that 
direction in the light of its good relations with Russia. 
  "We also discussed a number of issues directly in connection 
with Bosnia-Herzegovina and Iran. I thanked Iran, the Iranian 
Government, and the people for their support and aid that they 
have been giving to our country [words indistinct]. In that 
regard Iran right from the outset [passage indistinct]." 

</TEXT>

