<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Army Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2703211194 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2703211194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Alija Izetbegovic, president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, held a meeting in Sarajevo today 
with the top military leadership and the top representatives of 
the Ministry of Internal Affairs led by Army General Delic and 
Interior Minister Alispahic. The meeting was also attended by 
General Enver Hadzihasanovic, Bosnia-Herzegovina Army chief of 
staff brigadier, corps commanders of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army, and the commander of special units of the Ministry of 
Internal Affairs. 
  The following issues of importance for further development 
of 
the armed forces of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina were 
examined at the meeting: 
  -- The organizational set-up of the army of the federation 
of 
the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina in line with the Washington 
agreement and military agreements signed in Split, Zagreb, and 
Sarajevo; 
  -- Material support for the development of the armed forces 
and the search for appropriate solutions for training and 
strengthening all segments of defense of the federation of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina; 
  -- Resolution of the status of war invalids and families of 
fallen soldiers. 
  The military top leadership and the representatives of the 
Ministry of Internal Affairs gave their full support to Alija 
Izetbegovic, president of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, in 
his further political activities aimed at the founding of the 
federation of Bosnia-Herzegovina. They unequivocally supported 
the standpoint that territories taken by force and ethnically 
cleansed areas where genocide was perpetrated must be returned. 
  Other current issues were discussed at the meeting, on which 
the General Staff of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the 
Ministry of Internal Affairs expressed the same views. 

</TEXT>

