<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik Asserts Serb Right to Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2703180294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1751 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2703180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 27 Mar (TANJUG) -- "We cannot claim what 
is not ours, but on the other hand, no one can take away from us 
what our ancestors created and what has been given to us to 
preserve and cherish," Momcilo Krajisnik, president of the 
Srpska republic parliament, said today at a formal session of 
the Srpska assembly of Novo Sarajevo municipality. He added 
that, as a city, Serb Sarajevo was built on Serb areas and that 
Serbs have a right to it. 
  Thanking everyone who helped Serb Sarajevo preserve freedom 
and remain Serb, Krajisnik stressed that the struggle is not 
over yet, and that Serb enemies are still claiming the right to 
that part of the Serb ethnic territory. Krajisnik repeated that 
Serbs will not enter any kind of federation with Croats and 
Muslims, and that they will decide where and with whom to live 
on the basis of their right to self-determination. "We allow 
others to do everything we want to do, and if we are to be 
blamed for that, then we are guilty," Krajisnik said. 
  "Great pressure will be exerted on us to make further 
concessions. We can negotiate and find a compromise solution, 
but only so far as this will not threaten the minimum of our 
national interests. We cannot go below that, and we do not have 
the right to do that," Krajisnik said. 
  The deputies in the Srpska assembly of the Novo Sarajevo 
municipality and guests at today's formal session paid tribute 
to more than 1,200 victims -- half of whom were civilians -- who 
have fallen in defense of that part of Serb Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

