<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warns Against Deployment of Turks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2503232694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2258 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2503232694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 25 Mar (TANJUG) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, 
president of the people's assembly of the Srpska republic, this 
evening sent a letter to UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali, 
stressing that "a year ago the Srpska republic assembly passed a 
decision that no foreign army can enter its territory without 
the parliament's permission." 
  "Sending a Turkish military contingent to Bosnia would set a 
precedent which the Security Council should not accept, and 
should certainly not be the one to set it, because Turkey has 
failed to keep the necessary neutrality during the civil war in 
Bosnia, and it even openly sided with the Muslim side. In 
addition, Turkey is a country whose centuries-long 
occupation-style rule of this region is still alive in the 
memory of the Serb nation," the letter stresses. 
  Deputies of the Srpska republic's people's assembly believe, 
it is stated, that this decision is morally and humanly 
impermissible, and that it would be counterproductive for the 
peace process. 
  "The Srpska republic assembly charged me with warning you of 
fatal consequences of that action," Krajisnik stresses in his 
letter. 

</TEXT>

