<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Maglaj Croats Sever Ties With Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2603200194 Paris AFP in English 1932 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2603200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Michel Viatteau] </F>
  [Text] Maglaj, Bosnia-Herzegovina, March 26 (AFP) -- 
Bosnian Croats have severed their ties with their erstwhile Serb 
allies, with whom they had until recently been besieging the 
Moslem-held northern Bosnian town of Maglaj, a British UN 
officer said here Saturday. 
  Following the signing of the Croat-Moslem federation 
agreement in Washington March 18, the Croats had "found a means 
to convince" the Serb forces around Maglaj to leave, Major 
Richard Margesson, commander of British UN troops in Maglaj, 
said. 
  In Zepce, 18 kilometres (12 miles) south of Maglaj, a 
resident, who requested anonymity, said the Croat forces had 
simply paid off the Serbs, although it was not known if it was 
payment in kind or cash. 
  Margesson said that in the summer of 1993 the Croats in 
Zepce 
had feared they would not be able to repulse Bosnian army 
offensives coming from Zenica, Zavidovici and Maglaj. They "made 
an agreement" with the local Serb forces, who sent them several 
hundred soldiers in return for food, the chance to evacuate 
their sick and wounded, some military material and also cash, he 
said. 
  The Serb lines are still clearly visible 600 metres (yards) 
from the town centre, up on a hillside overlooking the city. 
From time to time, shots ring out, though not as frequently as 
before. On Friday, when a sniper targetted a British UN patrol, 
the UN shot back with 30-mm cannon fire, curtailing, at least 
for a while, further attacks. Since last Monday, the office of 
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has brought 
humanitarian aid convoys into the town and public soup kitchens, 
operating for the past two years, have started to wind down 
their aid operations as more people are able to cook for 
themselves at home. Rocket and mortar fire, which mark the walls 
of every building, only stopped 10 days ago. But despite the 
haunted looks in most people's eyes, the grim expressions, the 
lack of smiles, it seems as if the city is starting to breath 
again. Daniel de Schryver, head of mission for the Medecins sans 
Frontieres (Doctors without Borders) aid group, said the arrival 
of aid in the town had acted as a tremendous psychological boost. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9605 </DOCNO>
