<H3> <TI>   Serbs Stop U.S. Humanitarian Convoy to Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2503202094 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2503202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A convoy of the U.S. humanitarian organization (CRS) 
was stopped today along one of the recently opened blue roads 
from Visoko to Sarajevo at a control point of the Serbian 
aggressor's side near Ilijas. The reason the convoy was 
stopped, according to the announcement by the Information 
Ministry, was the demand by the Serbian side to be given 30 
percent of the goods from the convoy as a toll for passing 
through the territory under its control. 
  Such a gesture by the Serbian side at a time when the 
international community is exerting new efforts to find a 
peaceful solution for Bosnia-Herzegovina not only shows that 
these efforts are being ignored but that the aggressor has no 
intention of renouncing its blackmailing methods. By making it 
impossible for a convoy to pass through, one threatens the 
freedom and rights established by the agreement on opening blue 
corridors and thereby the basic principles of international 
humanitarian rights, it is said, among other things, in the 
information issued by the Information Ministry of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

