Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hamiz Deronjic from Brcko] </F>
  [Text] [Word indistinct] enemy air force, despite the 
resolutions of the UN Security Council, is constantly using the 
air corridors above temporarily occupied Brcko [words 
indistinct] chetnik pilots. At 1830 last night a Serbian 
helicopter that was flying on the Bjeljina-Pelagicevo route 
approached our positions and this [words indistinct] fire was 
opened. [Words indistinct] seriously damaged it was forced to 
land in temporarily occupied Brcko. 
  The demonstration of power of the enemy artillery on the 
Brcko plain in the absence of any attempts of infantry 
breakthroughs over the last few days reveals another chronic 
problem of the aggressor -- lack of manpower and low morale. 
According to our reliable sources, the chetnik soldiers on 
temporarily occupied Brcko territory, who have long been 
refusing to go to the front lines or into attacks, are now 
demanding that their commanders walk in front of them, because 
their commanders, infected with a feverish desire for military 
rank and prestige, have been marching them across minefields to 
satisfy their own ambitions. 

