<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kwasniewski on Coalition, Rosati Candidacy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2503182494 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1539 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2503182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 25 Mar--Following his Friday meeting with 
Waldemar Pawlak, Aleksander Kwasniewski told journalists that 
the coalition is maintaining Dariusz Rosati's candidacy to the 
post of deputy prime minister and finance minister. The prime 
minister believes his candidacy to be "professional, prepared, 
competent, and responsible" within this government, Kwasniewski 
said. 
  The president's objections connected to the FOZZ [Foreign 
Debt Servicing Fund] affair are not substantive, and they are 
meaningless when confronted with official reports received by 
the prime minister from the prosecutor general and the head of 
the State Protection Office, which state that "there are no 
grounds why Rosati should not hold the highest government 
posts," Kwasniewski said. 
  In his opinion, the president is once again "not showing 
proper interest in stabilizing the situation in the country." 
The argument that someone is working abroad and is involved 
there with the process of transforming the economies of West 
European countries just does not hold water, he added. 
  "Everything is now in the hands of the prime minister," said 
Kwasniewski. He also assured his audience that Rosati would not 
make any hasty decision. 
  Should the prime minister receive an official letter from 
the 
president, we will be dealing with a new situation, but this 
will be a situation between the coalition and the president, 
declared Kwasniewski. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

