<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iliescu Pardons Communists, Ethnic Hungarians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2603191494 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1400 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2603191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At his weekly news conference today, Presidential 
Spokesman Ambassador Traian Chebeleu said that, in accordance 
with constitutional provisions, Romanian President Ion Iliescu 
has signed 24 individual pardons, including for those involved 
in the murders committed at Albesti, Zetea, and Dealul [villages 
in Transylvania where Romanian policemen were killed by ethnic 
Hungarians during the December 1989 events] and former candidate 
members of the former Political Executive Committee of the 
Romanian Communist Party. In reply to a question as to whether 
the pardons have anything to do with the visit of the Council of 
Europe rapporteurs, Chebeleu answered in the affirmative, to the 
extent that some of the rapporteurs have brought up the issue of 
certain interventions made by the Democratic Union of Hungarians 
in Romania [UDMR] in this respect. 
  In connection with President Iliescu's meeting with the 
chief 
editors of the main dailies on 21 March, Traian Chebeleu said 
that two letters are now being drafted to be sent to Petre Mihai 
Bacanu [chief editor of ROMANIA LIBERA] and Ion Cristoiu [chief 
editor of EVENIMENTUL ZILEI], explaining the exact purpose of 
the meeting. 
  The spokesman denied rumors that the government has revised 
its decision to appoint General Niculae Spiroiu as our country's 
representative at NATO headquarters in Brussels. 

</TEXT>

