<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb-Croat Talks Resume in Zagreb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903103394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1000 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cease-fire talks between the delegation of the 
Republic of Croatia and representatives of rebel Serbs from the 
UNPA [UN Protected Areas] zones resumed at 1100 in the Russian 
Embassy in Zagreb. These talks, which began 22 March, were 
adjourned because of additional consultations by both sides and 
consideration of the proposals which emerged during the talks. 
  Today's talks are being attended for the first time by 
Charles Redman, the special envoy of the U.S. President. 
Vitaliy Churkin, special envoy of the Russian president, and 
U.S. Ambassador to Croatia Peter Galbraith were also taking 
part. The Croatian delegation comprises Engineer Hrvoje Sarinic, 
Slavko Degoricija, Gen Petar Stipetic, Naval Captain Davor 
Domazet, Smiljana Reljic and Budimir Pleskina. The Serbs from 
the UNPA zones are being represented at the talks by Dusan 
Rakic, Slobodan Jarcevic, Mile Novakovic, and Aco Draca. 
  The meeting in the Russian Embassy is being chaired by 
representatives of the international conference on the former 
Yugoslavia, ambassadors Geert Ahrens and Kai Aide. The only 
subject of the talks, it has been announced, will be an 
agreement on a cease-fire and in this connection the separation 
of forces. 

</TEXT>

