<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims, Croats Step Up Attacks on Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903134594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1252 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903134594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, March 29 (TANJUG) -- Forces of the 
Bosnian Moslems and of the army of Bosnian Croats (HVO) have 
intensified their attacks on Serb positions and settlements in 
the central, northern and western parts of the ex-Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, Serb military sources announced 
on Tuesday. 
  The announcement said Moslem troops intensified mortar fire 
in the region of the central Bosnian town of Srbobran (formerly 
Donji Vakuf). It added that Moslems continued using infantry 
arms, anti-aircraft guns and rifle-launched rockets in their 
fierce attacks on Serb positions on the western Bosnian 
battlefronts of Bihac and Novi Grad (formerly Bosanski Novi). 
  In the Moslem attacks on Bihac, one Serb defender was killed 
and the Serb side was forced to fire back, but it did not 
respond to the attacks on Novi Grad where there were no 
casualties, the announcement said. It added that on Monday, 
after 13 days of fighting, the army of Bosnian Serbs stopped an 
offensive launched by Moslems on March 16 and aimed at capturing 
the central Bosnian heights of Kupres. Bosnian Serb troops 
pushed the Moslems back towards the nearby town of Bugojno up 
north. 
  The Moslem attack on the Kupres heights, as the Bosnian Serb 
military sources said, was planned as part of the offensive 
launched to seize the town of Srbobran and later the town of 
Jajce. 
  The sources cautioned against fresh fierce attacks by Moslem 
forces which were redeploying themselves towards Srbobran and 
Kupres, moving in there their men and materiel from Travnik and 
Gornji Vakuf, the central Bosnian towns where they had fought 
Bosnian Croats. 
  The sources said the army of Bosnian Croats overnight 
fiercely attacked the positions of Serb defenders in the 
northern Bosnian stretch of the Sava valley, especially those 
outside the Serb villages of Jenjic and Lepnica, but there were 
no casualties and the defenders had not responded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

