<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Rejects Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2803175594 Prague CTK in English 1441 GMT 28 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2803175594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 28 (CTK) -- Although the government 
coalition has agreed on the mechanism for senatorial elections, 
the opposition continues to oppose the filling of the Senate, 
the upper house in the Czech Parliament which is defined in the 
Constitution but has not yet been filled. 
  The coalition parties -- the Civic Democratic Party (ODS), 
the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA), the Christian Democratic 
Union-Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL), and the Christian 
Democratic Party (KDS) -- adopted a compromise proposal on 
Friday [25 March], according to which in this year's election 27 
large constituencies will each elect three senators. Each 
electoral district will be composed of three smaller ones, so 
that the total number of districts in the Czech Republic will be 
81. 
  Representatives of the deputies' group of the Left Bloc 
(LB), 
the Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM), and the Czech 
Social Democratic Party (CSSD) today told CTK they opposed the 
decision. 
  LB deputies' group chairman Jaroslav Ortman said the 
proposal 
was politically aimed and legally problematic, as it was not 
defined in the Constitution. He said the proposal testified 
that the coalition parties are pressing for the establishment of 
the Senate primarily to safeguard their power, adding that 
controversies between the coalition parties were ensuing from 
mutual fear. 
  The LB still holds the view that the provision providing for 
the establishment of the Senate should be struck from the 
Constitution, Ortman said. He said that the opinions of the 
president and the Constitutional Court were a sufficient 
safeguard against parliamentary decisions. 
  The KSCM still considers Senate elections an attempt on the 
part of the right to preserve at least part of its power in case 
the distribution of forces between the right and left changes 
after Chamber of Deputies (lower house) elections, KSCM 
spokeswoman Vera Zezulkova told CTK. She said the KSCM rejected 
the Senate, but should a senatorial election be held it 
considered it more democratic to define the length of senators' 
terms of office through the election but not through casting of 
lots. The Communists consider the majority electoral system to 
be discrimination against opposition parties, she added. 
  CSSD Chairman Milos Zeman considers the discussion on 
different variants for senatorial elections "unrealistic," since 
the parliament has not yet decided whether or not it would 
exist. Zeman told CTK that the Social Democrats had submitted a 
bill on the abolition of the Senate to parliament and they 
intended to discuss the coalition's proposal only if their bill 
is rejected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

