<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   ODS Backs One-Mandate Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903123194 Prague CTK in English 1154 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903123194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 29 (CTK) -- The Civic Democratic 
Party (ODS) will continue to push for Senate elections in 81 
one-mandate constituencies, ODS spokeswoman Jana Petrova told 
journalists after today's meeting of the ODS leadership. 
  That means that the ODS (66 deputies in the 200-seat 
parliament) will insist on its stand although some ODS deputies 
spoke with their coalition colleagues about a possible 
compromise on Friday [25 March]. The ODS has favored that this 
year it would be determined what senators would be elected for 
two, four or six years. 
  The coalition is divided over the issue, as the minor 
parties, the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA, 14 deputies), the 
Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL, 
15) and the Christian Democratic Party (KDS, 10) prefer a 
different system consisting of 27 three-mandate constituencies. 
  The opposition is against having a Senate at all and is 
calling for its abolition. 
  "This is the only way to apply the electoral system 
stipulated by the Czech Constitution," Petrova stressed. 
  During Monday's coalition talks Premier and ODS Chairman 
Vaclav Klaus told his partners that his party had not been fully 
informed on the steps of some of its deputies regarding the 
compromise. Today the ODS leadership appointed Klaus to deal 
with the coalition partners on the issue. 

</TEXT>

