<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel Affirms Unions Have Right To Demonstrate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2803102394 Prague CTK in English 1457 GMT 27 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2803102394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 27 (CTK) -- The right to demonstrate 
cannot be taken away from the unions, Czech President Vaclav 
Havel said today on Czech Radio in his regular Sunday talk from 
Lany. 
  Demonstrations are a traditional tool not only of the 
unions, 
he said, adding that "demonstrations belong to democracy and 
democratic political culture as one of the ways people express 
themselves." Havel said this was why he would not see the 
union-organized Old Town Square demonstration last Tuesday [22 
March] as problematic. 
  In the event, union members, who came to Prague from all 
over 
the Czech Republic in 400 buses, and filled most of the square, 
protested against the employment bill which they saw as leading 
to worsening working and social conditions. The bill was passed 
by parliament last Wednesday [23 March]. 
  "On the other hand, I became aware of still how much our 
unions have to learn to demonstrate in a cultured way," Havel 
said, adding that throwing a stone or saying that the Minister 
(of Employment and Social Affairs Jindrich Vodicka, who was 
prevented by the crowd from addressing the rally) should not 
have come, were "not good signs." "This proves we all have to 
learn political culture," Havel said. 

</TEXT>

