<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cibulka Insists on Being Tried </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2803155794 Prague CTK in English 1250 GMT 28 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2803155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Brno, South Moravia, March 28 (CTK) -- Petr 
Cibulka, publisher of the NECENZUROVANE NOVINY [UNCENSORED 
NEWS], insists on being tried. He said this immediately after 
he learnt that Czech President had ordered the cessation of 
criminal proceedings for defamation of the president of the 
republic. [passage omitted] 
  "I fundamentally disagree with the cessation of criminal 
proceedings for the opinion expressed in evaluation of Vaclav 
Havel's political activities after November 17, 1989 (the day 
when the anti-communist "velvet" revolution began in 
Czechoslovakia)," Cibulka told CTK. 
  "Unlike communist criminals, StB [communist-era secret 
police] officers, judges, prosecutors, prison guards, and 
exponents of communist nomenclatura, who still remain unpunished 
and rule firmly over us, there is nothing I could be blamed 
for," Cibulka stressed. 
  He added he wanted to use the trial to "accuse the 
communist-velvet oligarchy, headed by Vaclav Havel, of covering 
numerous crimes," noting that "those covering criminals are 
criminals themselves." 

</TEXT>

