<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRY's Jovanovic on Relations, Democratization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903105094 Budapest MTI in English 0735 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 29 Mar (MTI) -- "A new, favourable 
process can begin in the Hungarian-Yugoslav relation," Yugoslav 
Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic said, in an interview 
carried in the Tuesday issue of NEPSZABADSAG. Jovanovic gave 
the interview when he made a brief stop in Budapest during his 
travels. 
  In answer to a question, he said the peace and security of 
the Balkan peninsula should be created, but not to the detriment 
of the Serbs. 
  When asked whether the democratization process of Serbia, 
which the international community expects from the settlement of 
the South Slav crisis, has begun or not, Jovanovic said: 
  "The process of democratization is well advanced in 
Yugoslavia. Yugoslavia, that is Serbia, is the only country in 
Eastern Europe which has held three parliamentary elections. If 
the declaration of the people's wish is the chief standard of a 
society's democratic character, then in our case there are no 
grounds for such verdicts, whereby the democratization of 
Yugoslavia is insufficient." 
  As regards his evaluation of Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza 
Jeszenszky's recent visit to Belgrade, Jovanovic said: "It is a 
particularly welcome fact that Jeszenszky's Belgrade visit was 
held in the spirit of mutual confidence. We believe that this 
implies the beginning of a process, which will result in the 
intensification of mutual confidence, political relations and 
the various cooperation forms." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

