<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jeszenszky: Russian Policy Poses `No Danger' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2703184694 Budapest MTI in English 1716 GMT 27 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2703184694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, March 27 (MTI) -- Hungarian Foreign 
Minister Geza Jeszenszky attended a public forum at Sarvar, 
western Hungary, on Sunday [27 March]. The minister expressed 
his trust in Russia's foreign policy, and said that peace 
partnership would provide a good framework for reducing 
anti-Western prejudice in Russians. In his view, Russia's more 
active foreign policy poses no danger to the region. If this 
policy aims to restore peace in the Balkans, it is welcomed by 
all, Jeszenszky said. 
  The minister mentioned that Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin would visit Budapest next week. 
  Russian Patriarch Aleksey II, who visited Hungary recently, 
could also experience that both the Hungarian people and 
policy-makers are eager to strengthen economic relations with 
Russia, Jeszenszky said. 
  Concerning the new Slovak government, the minister said that 
Hungary is ready to pursue a policy of extended arms. Should 
someone grasp this arm, it would be fortunate not only for the 
two countries but even for Europe as a whole, he said. 

</TEXT>

