<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hungarian President Goncz Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets With President Walesa </H4>
<F P=102> AU2903074094 Budapest MTI in English 1758 GMT 28 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 28 Mar (MTI) -- Hungarian President Arpad 
Goncz and Polish President Lech Walesa talked in Warsaw on 
Monday. Both presidents felt that Hungarian-Polish friendship 
could stabilise the Visegrad pact (Hungary, Poland, the Czech 
Republic, and Slovakia), and European integration efforts. 
  On Monday at his residence, President Goncz received the 
representatives of Podkowa Lesna town, near Warsaw, which was 
one of the main centres of Polish opposition in the 1980s. 
Parish priest Leon Kantorski figured prominently in this, and 
the Hungarian president presented him with the Imre Nagy 
Memorial Plaque. President Goncz presented the Pro Cultura 
Hungaria Memorial Medal to the Chairman of the Federation of 
Polish-Hungarian Friendship Societies. In the afternoon, the 
Hungarian president received Polish Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski. 
  President Goncz also paid a visit to the Polish Parliament. 
He met leaders of the parliamentary clubs, the chairman of the 
foreign affairs and economic committees of both Houses, and 
members of the Polish-Hungarian group of the Interparliamentary 
Union. He said Hungary sees closer cooperation with countries in 
the region as vital, with Poland as its closest partner in the 
region. The president also valued the Visegrad group, and 
thought that the earliest possible introduction of the Central 
European free trade bloc is a basic condition of a trade boom. 
The Hungarian president then met Jozef Oleksy, marshall of the 
Sejm, and with Zofia Kuratowska, deputy marshall of the Senate. 

</TEXT>

