<H3> <TI>   Hungarian President Goncz Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Regional Cooperation Stressed </H4>
<F P=102> LD2803115394 Warsaw PAP in English 1111 GMT 28 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2803115394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, March 28 -- President Lech Walesa on Monday 
met with Hungarian President Arpad Goncz at the start of his 
three-day official visit to Poland. "I would like to expand our 
cooperation, it is possible and even necessary," the Polish 
president said at the start of the talks. 
  Both presidents agreed that regional cooperation is a 
"supreme goal" of Central European countries. President Goncz 
stressed that despite internal problems, the Visegrad Group has 
stable prospects for development in the future. 
  Polish-Hungarian plenary talks focused on economic issues. 
Representatives of both countries stressed the necessity to 
rebuild Polish-Hungarian trade contacts. Turnover between the 
two countries dropped from 450 million dollars in 1991 to 200 
million 1993. 

</TEXT>

