<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hungarian President Goncz Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Holds News Conference </H4>
<F P=102> LD2903113394 Warsaw PAP in English 1020 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2903113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, March 29 -- Hungarian President Arpad Goncz 
said Tuesday that Poland and Hungary have agreed on all vital 
issues, summing up his talks with President Lech Walesa, Prime 
Minister Waldemar Pawlak and other Polish officials during his 
short official visit to Poland. 
  Goncz, holding a press conference, said Poland and Hungary 
are linked by the common goal of quick integration with Western 
Europe, through European Union membership as well as through 
cooperation in other fields of international political life. 
  He stressed the importance of regional cooperation, 
including 
cooperation within the Visegrad group. "There should be a 
multicolour Europe of regions, while our integration with 
European structures would serve Europe as a whole as well as our 
region," said Goncz. 
  "We have not discussed military cooperation during this 
visit," the president said adding, however, that there are wide 
possibilities of cooperation between Polish and Hungarian arms 
industries. He said he discussed with Polish partners such 
cooperation and the difficult financial situation of those 
industries in both countries. 
  Arpad Goncz assured the Polish hosts that there will be no 
return to the old system after May elections in Hungary 
"irrespective who wins the elections... Hungary's foreign 
policy, approach towards the economy and Polish-Hungarian 
relations will remain unchanged." He added that "for Hungary, 
Poland, ruled by the left, elected in democratic elections, 
remains to be the same partner as it had been before." 

</TEXT>

