<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nastase Claims PDSR Against Early Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903120594 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 0955 GMT 29 Mar 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, ROMPRES, 29/3/1994 -- "The ruling Party 
of Social Democracy does not wish early elections," said the 
PDSR Executive President Adrian Nastase, in an interview with 
the governmental daily VOCEA ROMANIEI. Early elections at the 
time being "would hinder Romania's political and economic 
functioning," opined Adrian Nastase. 
  The PSDR leader said also that the PSDR could reasonably 
consider the opportunity of local elections as much as certain 
political forces were asking for general elections. By the time 
of the local elections of February 1992, the PSDR had not been 
formed yet, reminded Adrian Nastase. As the local authorities 
are the ones to administer the general elections, the ruling 
party would have no degree of involvement in the territory in 
case of early parliamentary elections, said Nastase. The PSDR 
would therefore assign a higher priority to early local 
elections, ahead of general elections. 
  The PSDR leader reminded also that the recent polls 
confirmed 
that the PSDR had maintained its popularity with the electorate 
as revealed by the past parliamentary elections of September 
1992, some 28 percent. 

</TEXT>

