<H3> <TI>   Cernak Elected Chairman of New Democratic Party </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2703132294 Prague CTK in English 2100 GMT 26 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2703132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zvolen, central Slovakia, March 26 (CTK) -- Ludovit 
Cernak was elected chairman of the newly-established National 
Democratic Party-New Alternative (NDS-NA). At an NDS-NA 
constituent congress vote here today, Cernak received 136 votes 
out of a total of 137 cast. Cernak, former chairman of the 
Slovak National Party (SNS), was the only candidate for the 
post. Delegates to the constituent conference of the National 
Democratic Party-New Alternative (NDS-NA) decided that the 
party, which declared itself a conservative one, would seek 
admission to the European Democratic Union (EDU). 
  According to preliminary consultations, the Christian 
Democratic Movement (KDH) and some conservative parties of the 
Visegrad group countries (the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland 
and Slovakia), which are EDU members, would support the 
newly-established party in its effort. 
  Cernak said the party intended to cooperate with Czech 
members of the EDU -- the ruling Civic Democratic Party (ODS) 
and the government coalition Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA). 
The NDS-NA would run for the forthcoming early elections in a 
coalition with the Alliance of Slovak Democrats (ADSR) of 
ex-Foreign Minister Milan Knazko and the Slovak Democratic Union 
(DUS) of Premier Jozef Moravcik. Negotiations are underway with 
the Greens Party on its participation in the pre-election 
coalition bloc. 
  The party's primary goal is preparation of coupon 
privatisation. Privatisation Minister Milan Janicina said he 
sought to speed up privatisation in such a way that it became 
irreversible. Coupon privatisation is to concern 80 to 100 
billion crowns (2.6 to 3.3 billion USD) worth of property. 

</TEXT>

