<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cernak: Centrist Parties Will Not Merge </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2603203594 Prague CTK in English 1742 GMT 25 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2603203594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 25 (CTK) -- Differing foreign 
orientation and the dilemma of the "selective" membership or a 
wide membership prevents from creating one party composed of 
three groupings represented in Moravcik's cabinet, chairman of 
the preparatory committee of the National Democratic Party-New 
Alternative (NDS-NA) Ludovit Cernak said. The groupings, the 
"Centric Bloc" consists of "dissidents" from former Premier 
Vladimir Meciar's Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) and 
Slovak National Party (SNS): the Alliance of Slovak Democrats 
(AD SR), led by former Foreign Minister Milan Knazko, the 
Democratic Union of Slovakia (DUS) of current Premier Jozef 
Moravcik and Cernak's NDS-NA. The centrists, who have seven 
posts in Moravcik's eighteen-member cabinet, are holding a 
constituent congress on Saturday [26 March]. "The NDS-NA's place 
will be right of center of the political spectrum; it should 
head towards the European Democratic Union," said Cernak, former 
SNS chairman. The latest poll gives 1.3 percent for Cernak's 
party, while the AD SR would receive 1.2 percent of votes. 

</TEXT>

