<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accord Reached With Czechs on Food Certificates </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2803155094 Prague CTK in English 1203 GMT 28 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2803155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 28 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic 
and Slovakia have reached agreement to mutually recognize food 
quality certificates under the condition that Slovakia amends 
its customs law, one of the participants in today's meeting of 
the Customs Union Council told CTK. He added the amendment 
could have the form of a certificates clause to the Czech-Slovak 
payments agreement. 
  Another condition is the conclusion of an inter-state 
agreement dealing with cases involving certificated foodstuffs 
which would not meet the prescribed quality. A commission of 
experts is to be set up to make out the list of "sensitive 
items" and to define conditions of their exchanges. 
  The above measures do not apply to re-exported goods whose 
import is possible only if accompanied by certificates from the 
importing country. 
  Measures facilitating the implementation of the agreement 
are 
to be worked out by May 1, the date until which Slovakia had for 
the time being postponed the realization of its request for 
obligatory food certification. 
  Slovakia started to require certificates for food imports on 
February 11. One week later, on the request from Prague, it 
suspended the measure temporarily. Later, the former government 
of Vladimir Meciar said it would reintroduce the certificate 
request as from April 1, but the new government of Jozef 
Moravcik, which was appointed on March 16, postponed the measure 
minimally until May 1. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

