<F P=101> Yugoslavia, Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Seize Passport, Impose Fine on Scholar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2703132694 Tirana ATA in English 1112 GMT 26 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2703132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prishtina, March 26 (ATA) -- Since October 18 of 
the last year, Serbian authorities have taken the passport, 
blocked the phone of Rexhep Qosja, academician and writer, 
practically putting him into home arrest, the ATA reporter in 
Prishtina reports. 
  ATA reporter said that when Serbian authorities banned the 
Albanalogic Institute, they gave a decision to Mr. Qosja 
according to which he must be taken the passport and pay a 3,000 
DM [German marks] fine. This is the biggest punishment for 
passing the border with Albania without exit visas. The 
punishment is applied by Yugoslavia since 1981 in order to stop 
any kind of communication between the Albanians who are 
separated by Albania-Kosova border which is under Serbian forces 
control. 
  The Council for Human Rights Protection in Prishtina, the 
Albanian Intellectuals Forum, and the Albanalogic Institute 
appeal to the international community for stopping the 
repression on Albanians of Kosova and taking the passports from 
them. 

</TEXT>

