<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel, ODA Agree on Senate Election Compromise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2803100294 Prague CTK in English 1639 GMT 26 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2803100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 26 (CTK) -- Czech President Vaclav 
Havel and the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA) Deputy Group 
representatives agreed that the compromise solution of the 
Senate election key worked out by the coalition representatives 
on Friday [25 March] might be a good working proposition for 
drafting the parliament and senate election bill, ODA Deputy 
Group Chairman Oldrich Kuzilek told journalists today after the 
meeting with Havel. 
  Kuzilek said the ODA deputies also told Havel about their 
attitude towards the issue of Jewish property restitution. The 
ODA-proposed amendments to the out-of-court rehabilitation 
settlement and land laws are not seen by the ODA deputies as a 
breach of the 1948 restitution deadline. "All it takes is to be 
well versed in the 1950s statutes," Kuzilek said. The amendment 
only seeks that all which ought to have been restituted under 
the law was restituted, he added. 
  Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD) Deputy Group Chairman 
Karel Hrdy said that he told Havel about an amendment to local 
election law. The CSSD pushes for a proportionate and simple 
majority combination election system, he said he told Havel. 
CSSD Deputy Petra Buzkova said they also consulted the question 
of pensionable age with Havel. 
  Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party 
(KDU-CSL) Deputy Group representative and deputy chairman of 
parliament Jan Kasal said that Havel was open to the idea of 
"three times and no more," a short for sentencing to life 
without the possibility of parole habitual offenders on a third 
conviction of a listed violent crime. Havel agreed, adding, 
however, that even such convicts should be allowed the chances 
of re-socialisation under strict conditions still to be worked 
out, Kasal said. 
  Havel also agreed that alternative punishment for light 
crimes, namely community work, become part of the criminal code, 
Kasal said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

