<H3> <TI>   German Defense Minister Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903131694 Sofia BTA in English 1249 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, March 29 (BTA) -- German Federal Minister of 
Defence Volker Ruehe, who came on an official three-day visit to 
Sofia at the head of a German military delegation yesterday, was 
received by Deputy Prime Minister Evgeni Matinchev and First 
Deputy Foreign Minister Valentin Gatsinski. 
  Mr. Matinchev familiarized Mr. Ruehe with the political 
priorities of the Bulgarian Government, the difficulties in 
implementing the economic reform and Bulgaria's losses ensuing 
from the Yugo-embargo. Mr. Matinchev emphasized that Bulgaria 
attaches paramount importance to Germany's support in settling 
its external debt problem by signing arrangements with the Paris 
and the London clubs, the Government Press Office said. Mr. 
Ruehe said that following the processes in Bulgaria, the German 
Government sees some positive signs. In answer to the Bulgarian 
Government's request that Germany ratify Bulgaria's Europe 
Agreement before the summer recess of the Bundestag, Mr. Ruehe 
said that the agreement had already been endorsed by the 
Committee on Foreign Policy and was now being considered by the 
Economic Committee. According to Mr. Ruehe, the German 
Government will do its best to help Bulgaria resolve its 
financial problems in the shortest possible time. 
  Today the German military delegation had a meeting with 
First 
Deputy Foreign Minister Valentin Gatsinski. They discussed 
issues concerning Bulgaria's relations with its neighbours and 
Russia, the situation in the Balkans, the possibilities for 
strengthening security in the region, and the Partnership for 
Peace plan. In connection with the inclusion of Turkish troops 
in the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] forces in Bosnia, Mr. 
Gatsinski confirmed the Bulgarian position that no Balkan 
countries should intervene in the Bosnia-Herzegovina conflict in 
any form. 

</TEXT>

