<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   ODS Senate Proposal Criticized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903160794 Prague CTK in English 1420 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 29 (CTK) -- The system of 81 
one-mandate constituencies for Senate elections on which the 
Civic Democratic Party (ODS) insists could bring regional 
deviations during the elections and destabilize the political 
spectrum, the Christian Democratic Party (KDS) says in a 
statement given to CTK today. 
  The statement has come in reaction to today's meeting of the 
leadership of the ODS, the strongest party in the government 
coalition, which confirmed ODS's intention to push for Senate 
elections in 81 one-mandate constituencies, although other 
coalition parties, including the KDS, prefer a system of 27 
three-mandate constituencies. 
  The KDS is disappointed that the ODS is not willing to 
discuss other variants for Senate elections, the statement says. 
It adds, however, that regardless its reservations towards the 
ODS's stand the "KDS respects the Czech Constitution" and 
considers it more important that the Constitution be observed 
than that its own model of Senate elections be implemented. 
  The Senate, an upper house of the Czech Parliament, is 
defined in the Constitution but has not yet been filled. 

</TEXT>

