<H3> <TI>   Deputy Wants Information on Communist Property </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903154194 Prague CTK in English 1349 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brno, South Moravia, March 29 (CTK) -- Parliament 
has so far received no information about the return of the 
property of the former Communist Party of Czechoslovakia (KSC), 
which was decided on by a federal parliament law of 1990, deputy 
Jiri Karas told journalists today. 
  The process had obviously been impeded by problems of 
economic reform and the division of Czechoslovakia but, he said, 
"it should still be stated what has been done with the 
property." He said he had submitted questions to Economics 
Minister Karel Dyba, to which he expected answers within 30 days. 
  In 1990 the KSC property was reckoned to be worth some 30 
billion crowns but current estimates rate it at around 13 
billion ($433 million). Karas himself believes the value of the 
property to be 15 or 16 billion crowns, although no inventory 
has been drawn up. 

</TEXT>

