<H3> <TI>   Hungarian President Ends Visit, Departs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003130394 Warsaw PAP in English 1245 GMT 30 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD3003130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Krakow, March 30 -- Hungarian President Arpad Goncz 
on Wednesday ended his Polish visit and left for Budapest from 
Krakow where earlier in the day he had toured the Wawel Royal 
Castle and met with professors and students of the Jagiellonian 
University. 
  Addressing a news conference at the university, Goncz 
stressed that politically "Poland and Hungary want to become a 
part of Europe," but culturally "the two countries have always 
been its part." 
  "We will submit European Union full membership motions at 
the 
same time which proves that we are the two pillars of the 
European stability," he said. 
  Speaking about a cooperation between Poland and Hungary, 
Goncz stated that it has interesting prospects, as "future 
Europe is not only the Europe of nations but also of regions." 
  The Hungarian head of state added that the Visegrad Group 
states, including Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic and 
Slovakia, should go together on the road to a new Europe and 
that this cooperation does not need to be institutionalized. 

</TEXT>

