<H3> <TI>   Canadian Ministers Visit, Review Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903210294 Warsaw PAP in English 1956 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2903210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, March 29 -- Canada's Minister of Foreign 
Affairs Andre Ouellet and Polish foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski reviewed on Tuesday Polish-Canadian bilateral 
relations. On Wednesday, delegations of the two countries are 
expected to hold plenary talks. 
  The Canadian minister supported Poland's efforts for NATO 
membership, and the sides discussed Canada's possible assistance 
in the implementation of the "Partnership for Peace" programme, 
an official in the Foreign Ministry said after the talks. 
  According to Ouellet, Poland should become a NATO member 
through the "Partnership for Peace," or closer relations with 
the Western European Union. During the talk, Minister 
Olechowski pointed to the fact that all threats to Poland can be 
at the same time threats to the stabilized situation in the 
world. 
  Earlier in the day, minister ouellet and director of the 
Ministry for Foreign Economic Relations Maciej Lesny discussed 
economic cooperation between their countries, possibilities of 
Canada's assistance for Polish farmers and access of Canadian 
goods to the Polish market. 

