<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agrarian Party To Promote `Neoliberal' Doctrine </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3003110994 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 0902 GMT 30 Mar 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3003110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 30/3/1994 -- The doctrine of the 
Romanian Democratic Agrarian Party [PDAR] and its position 
regarding the ruling political party are covered in an interview 
granted to the daily AZI by Agrarian Party's President Victor 
Surdu. 
  After the success scored in the 1992 local elections, the 
Romanian Democratic Agrarian Party, which had won then 15 
percent of the votes, had no similar performance in the 
parliamentary elections held the same year, currently holding 
representation only in the Senate. 
  Victor Surdu says: "We are looking for a new programme, 
based on the doctrine called modern agrarianism, of neoliberal 
concept, which sets property beyond everything. Starting from 
Romania's ties, we consider that we must gather all our efforts 
to solve the issues confronting Romania's agriculture such as 
involving a major number of extremely active people in the 
agriculture. If we start this important economic sector, job 
opportunities will show for almost 60 percent of the population, 
for which we could provide social protection and the dignity to 
have a job." 
  On the previous contacts with the ruling party and as 
regards 
the Agrarian Party's position as to the Vacaroiu cabinet, the 
Agrarian president said: "The dialogue with the Party of Social 
Democracy has led us to the conclusion that, if we cannot come 
into power, we are situated in the opposition which however 
supports the Vacaroiu government, but only under the provisions 
that government legislative decisions and initiatives would not 
run counter our programme." 
  "After the dialogue with all parliamentary parties, the 
ruling Party of Social Democracy should assume full 
responsibility for everything that happens in Romania at 
present," Victor Surdu was quoted as saying. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

