<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Voters Dissatisfied With Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2903154494 Prague CTK in English 1256 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 29 (CTK) -- Half of Slovaks are 
disappointed with the way the members of parliament they elected 
are representing them and defending their interests, the results 
of a Slovak Statistical Office [SUSR] poll shows. The 
proportion of respondents satisfied with the parties in 
parliament is 25 percent. 
  The poll also asked whether people would have supported the 
referendum which former Premier Vladimir Meciar intended to hold 
on the validity of the parliamentary mandate of deputies who 
left the party they were elected for. Twelve percent felt 
"maverick" deputies should lose their seats. 
  Eighty-two percent said they believed a deputy should vote 
according to his own conscience rather than be obliged to follow 
the party line. 
  When asked if deputies should vote in the interests of their 
party, 52 percent said yes and 40 percent said no. Comparing 
answers to the last two questions it follows that some 41 
percent of respondents agree with both statements together, 
indicating, according to SUSR, voters were not well informed 
about the debate surrounding deputies' mandates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

