<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Lilic Meets With Libyan Envoy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903162894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1216 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903162894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 29 March (TANJUG) -- Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia President Zoran Lilic today received special Libyan 
envoy 'Ali 'Abd-al-Salam al-Turyaki, who handed him a message 
from Libyan leader Colonel Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi. 
  Their talks focused on the further improvement of the 
already 
successful and friendly cooperation between the two countries, 
both in the bilateral and international fields. They paid 
particular attention to some aspects of economic cooperation. 
  Speaking about the Bosnia-Herzegovina crisis, President 
Lilic 
expressed the hope that we are not far from peace, which he said 
was a condition for stability in the entire region. President 
Lilic stressed that the FRY [Federal Republic of Yugoslavia] has 
nothing against the Muslim-Croat federation, provided that it is 
not to the detriment of the Serb side; he also said there would 
be neither a solution nor peace in this former Yugoslav republic 
without an equitable agreement reached between all three sides 
and the observance of the right of each of the nations to 
self-determination. 
  As regards the FRY, it will continue to strive in a 
persistent, active, and constructive way toward reaching a 
permanent and just resolution of the crisis on the territory of 
former Yugoslavia, as it has done since the very outset of the 
crisis, President Lilic concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

