<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Conditions for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903224794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2228 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903224794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 29 (TANJUG) -- President of the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia Zoran Lilic said on Tuesday that 
this country had nothing against a Moslem-Croat Federation in 
civil war torn Bosnia-Herzegovina provided it was not 
detrimental to the third side, the Serbs. 
  During the talks with special Libyan envoy 'Ali 'Abd 
al-Salam 
al-Turyaki, who presented to Lilic a message from Libyan leader 
Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi, Lilic said that there would be no peace 
in Bosnia without agreement on an equal footing between all 
three warring sides and without respect of the rights of every 
nation to self-determination. 
  A war of local Serbs, Croat and Moslems has been raging in 
the former Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina for almost 
two years. Croats and Moslems signed an agreement on a 
federation in mid-March under U.S. pressure. The question of 
the Serbs joining the federation has remained open, but 
representatives of this people on several occasions pointed out 
that the recognition of the right to self-determination of 
Moslems and Croats meant that Serbs had the same right as well. 
The Serbs in Bosnia-Herzegovina have proclaimed their own state 
which covers round 70 percent of the territory of this former 
Yugoslav republic. 
  Lilic expressed hope that peace in Bosnia was not far, 
saying 
it was a precondition for stability in the entire region. The 
better part of the talks between the Yugoslav president and the 
Libyan envoy was devoted to the promotion of the already 
successful bilateral cooperation, especially in the area of 
economics. The Libyan envoy was also received today by Yugoslav 
Minister for Foreign Trade Relations Milorad Unkovic. Al-Turyaki 
expressed Libya's readiness to send humanitarian aid to 
Yugoslavia through Red Cross organizations. He said that this 
was a symbolic act with which Libya wished to show good will and 
understanding for its old friend -- Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

