<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Discusses Coalition Talks, EC Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903185794 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus by Lucie </F>
Weissova in Prague on 29 March--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Weissova] Prime Minister, representatives of 
the coalition parties held yet another meeting yesterday because 
there have been rumors that there are some clashes in the 
coalition. Jan Kalvoda, for instance, said a few days ago that 
he was dissatisfied with the method of communication in the 
coalition. I would like to ask you whether things have cleared 
up after the meeting and whether you reached a consensus on the 
disputed issues. 
  [Klaus] No agreement has been reached because the 
differences 
are not caused by lack of communication. This is simply a rumor 
that is being constantly spread around by someone. The 
differences exist because of differing views, because of 
differing approaches to the various issues we are currently 
facing. Naturally, these differences do not apply to the 95 
percent of matters of everyday importance. 
  The differences lie in several evergreens, so to speak. On 
the one hand, there are the restitution-related issues, and, on 
the other, there is the creation of the senate, a new chamber in 
our parliament. In my view, the need for this chamber is very 
disputable. The third issue is formed by the contentious 
problems related to the regional setup, the issues that stir the 
whole country. 
  Thus our views do indeed differ, and in no case can they be 
related to lack of communication. 
  [Weissova] Let us return to your recent visit to Finland. In 
your own words, one of the experiences you brought with you from 
there was that the admission into the European Union does not 
need to be a cure all, and that, especially at the beginning, it 
might bring certain disadvantages. Does this mean that you 
share with the so-called Euroskeptics their worries about the 
Brussels bureaucracy, which, by the way, is formed mainly by 
people from governing European Socialist parties? 
  [Klaus] [passage omitted] This bureaucracy is not a 
fundamental problem of the European Community. It is, rather, a 
complementary problem that is above the fundamental problem. In 
my view, the fundamental question is something else: what the 
concept of European integration is, to what degree it really 
means a general opening of various obstacles, movements of 
people, ideas, goods, money, and various other things all over 
Europe--which we support wholeheartedly--and to what extent it 
is an attempt to force upon people a specific ideology, specific 
unity, specific compulsory common solutions, and thousands of 
other things. This is not Euroskeptism; this is Eurorealism. 
This is simply searching for a sensible social setup in Europe. 
I always say that the important thing is not whether there will 
be 12 or 16 or 20 countries, but what system of relations 
between the individual and the state will prevail in this 
situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

