<H3> <TI>   Croats `Torching' Serb Villages in Zadar Region </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003202094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1945 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3003202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 30 Mar (TANJUG) -- The village of Islam 
Grcki and a part of the village of Kasic in the Zadar 
hinterland, which are still controlled by the Croatian forces 
and which should be returned to the republic of Serb Krajina 
according to the cease-fire agreement signed in Zagreb last 
night, were in flames at around 1900 this evening, ISKRA 
[Krajina Serb news agency] has reported. 
  This news caused anger among the Serb fighters in the area 
of 
Benkovac who wanted to retaliate by attacking Croatian troops 
because of this barbarism. As ISKRA has learned from the Serb 
Krajina army liaison officer, Mladen Kalapac, the Serb side 
immediately reacted by demanding an immediate halt to the 
torching of the Serb villages. 
  UN Protection Force representatives promised they would most 
urgently get involved in preventing the torching of the villages 
of Kasic and Islam Grcki. 

</TEXT>

