<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parlacen Decries U.S. Plan To Charge Asylum-Seekers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2502222794 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2104 GMT 25 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2502222794 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 25 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- The Central 
American Parliament (Parlacen) today denounced the charging of a 
$130 fee to people who request political asylum in the United 
States -- an action the U.S. Government plans to put into 
practice in the near future. Parlacen President Jose Guerrero, 
who is a Salvadoran citizen, responded bitterly to the U.S. 
initiative, arguing that it goes against international 
agreements on the right to political asylum. 
  Last week, the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service 
[INS] announced the U.S. Government's intention to charge a fee 
to people who request political asylum to reduce INS expenses. 
The INS currently has more than 360,000 pending asylum 
requests. U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno explained a few days 
ago that the fee will only be charged to those people who can 
afford to pay it and that it will not be mandatory. 
  Nevertheless, the Parlacen president asserted, "To charge 
for 
political asylum is to exploit and profit from a human right we 
all have." Guerrero called the U.S. Government initiative 
"illogical," noting that it is being implemented "now in the 
1990's, when there is a worldwide effort to strengthen human 
rights." Guerrero stressed that the United States will be the 
only country in the world charging for political asylum if the 
measure goes into effect. 
  Gregg Breyer, the national director of the INS Asylum 
Office, 
has reported that his office is "flooded" with false petitions 
for political asylum and that petitioners know the chances are 
slim they will be deported. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

