<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mulino Comments on OAS Election, U.S. Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2602202594 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 26 Feb 94 p 2A </F>
<F P=103> PA2602202594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Lastenia Murillo Munoz] </F>
  [Text] Panamanian Foreign Minister Raul Mulino said 
yesterday that Panama continues to support Costa Rican Foreign 
Minister Bernd Niehaus unconditionally in his aspiration for the 
position of OAS Secretary General. Mulino added that a pledged 
word "is written in stone," even if it is misinterpreted later. 
  Mulino said that groundless reports on this subject have 
been 
spread because, when Panama offered to support the Costa Rican 
Government, Colombian President Cesar Gaviria's candidacy was 
anything but decided. 
  Colombian Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin de Rubio visited 
Panama for a few hours to promote Gaviria's candidacy to this 
position, but Panama had already pledged its word for Costa Rica. 
  According to Mulino, the U.S. position in promoting 
Gaviria's 
candidacy cannot be interpreted as "blackmail. Whether we like 
it or not, the United States is a country on our continent with 
the full right to vote for whichever candidate it chooses," 
Mulino said finally. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

