<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Endara, Gaviria Issue Joint Declaration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2502175994 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 24 Feb 94 p 1A </F>
<F P=103> PA2502175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vilma E. Figueroa B.] </F>
  [Text] President Guillermo Endara of Panama and President 
Cesar Gaviria of Colombia have signed a joint declaration at the 
fourth meeting of the Colombian-Panamanian neighbors' 
commission. The two presidents signed the Transfer of Convicted 
Individuals Treaty, the Illegal Immigrants Agreement, and the 
Complementary Protocol on the Legal Assistant and Mutual 
Cooperation Agreement in Medellin. They also created the 
Permanent Commission for the Demarcation of the 
Colombian-Panamanian Border at the meeting. This commission will 
hold its first technical meeting in Santa Fe de Bogota on 17 and 
18 March. 
  In one of the paragraphs of the joint declaration, President 
Gaviria reiterated his satisfaction with Panama's efforts for 
the orderly transfer of the Panama Canal, which will occur on 31 
December 1999, and the canal's administration. According to a 
press note released by the Panamanian Presidency, the two 
presidents expressed their firm conviction that a full and 
participative democracy is the appropriate framework to meet the 
people's needs. They also agreed that social development 
programs strengthen democracy and that fighting poverty is a 
priority. 
  An ANSA dispatch, datelined Medellin, reports that yesterday 
Gaviria stressed the need for Colombia and Panama to consolidate 
their integration and cooperation to fight drug trafficking 
jointly. He maintained that "the big effort" the two countries 
are making to confront drug trafficking would be greatly 
rewarded "if we were able to strengthen coordination and 
cooperation between our nations' authorities on a permanent 
basis. Colombia and Panama have a great opportunity to fight 
this scourge; we can do more to make this threat disappear 
forever," Gaviria said at the opening of the fourth meeting of 
the Colombian-Panamanian neighbors' commission. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9883 </DOCNO>
